name: 5-chlorovanillic acid
Reason:
The target compound, 5-chlorovanillic acid, can be broken down into different functional groups and their influence on the melting point can be considered quantitatively. The basic unit here is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C.
 Methoxy group (-OCH3): This electron-donating group generally increases the melting point by improving intermolecular interactions through its ability to participate in dipole-dipole interactions. It could increase the melting point by +40°C.
 Hydroxy group (-OH): This group can form strong hydrogen bonds, significantly raising the melting point. This effect could be approximately +80°C.
 Carboxylic acid (-COOH): This highly polar group also forms strong hydrogen bonds and contributes to a marked rise in melting point. Its contribution could be +50°C.
 Chloro group (-Cl): A heavier halogen substituent like chlorine would typically increase the melting point due to the increased molecular weight and polarizability. This increases van der Waals interactions and can be estimated at + 20°C.
 Combined, the effects of these groups predict an increase in the melting point from the base benzene value.
Prediction: The predicted melting point would be the sum of the effects from these functional groups on top of the benzene base value: 5.5 (benzene) + 40 (methoxy) + 80 (hydroxy) + 50 (carboxylic acid) + 20 (chloro) = 195.5°C
